"Abstract Colin Tapper reviews the recent Law Commission Report on reform of the hearsay rule in civil proceedings so far as it relates to the reception of evidence of computer output. The reception in evidence of computer output has gone through three phases in the United Kingdom. At first computer output was rarely sought to be adduced in evidence, and such output was immediately recognisable as such. Then as computer usage, especially for word processing applications grew, so the demand for reception of such output rose to dimensions comparable to that of output produced by more conventional means, and for much the same reasons it became less easily distinguishable from it. Now preparation by means of a computer has become by far the most common means of producing documents, though the sophistication of appearance of such documents has perhaps resulted in their having become more recognisable again. It is to such practical considerations that the rules governing the reception of such evidence should be addressed. It is no good having special rules if the party adducing the document, usually its recipient, does not know whether to apply them or not."
